\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental Welfare Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the two theorems are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
First Fundamental Welfare Theorem: If a competitive equilibrium (Walrasian
 equilibrium) exists, then the equilibrium 1) is equal to a Pareto equilibrium;
 2) is Pareto optimal; or 3) leads to a Pareto efficient allocation of resources..
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that bullets 1), 2), and 3) are equivalent statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Second Fundamental Welfare Theorem: Any Pareto optimal equilibrium (or,
 any Pareto efficient allocation) can be sustained by a competitive equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall the assumptions needed for the Fundamental Welfare Theorems:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the Second Fundamental Welfare Theorem requires one more condition:
 convexity of preferences.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Complete markets: no unpriced goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
No market power: all economic agents are price-takers (competitive markets
 for all goods).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At the end of Econ 2020a, we discussed failures of this assumption: namely,
 monopolies and externalities.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Complete information for all agents.
 This assumption fails if we have uncertainty in the payoffs or when there
 is asymmetric or imperfect information.
 Information economics uses the tools of game theory to identify equilibrium
 when the complete information assumption fails.
 
\end_layout

