\begin_layout Section
Adverse Selection in Insurance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model Set-Up
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some people like to draw game trees, but I don't find them very helpful.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Risk averse consumer with wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and utility function equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $u(W)=\sqrt{W}$
\end_inset

.
 Two states of the world where in one state the consumer loses all of her
 wealth and in the second state there are no damages.
 Risk of losing everything is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim U[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 The timing of the model is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

: Nature determines type of consumer, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer knows her type.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is high, then the consumer is high risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

: Monopolist insurer determines the contract to be offered: insurer offers
 full insurance
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Full insurance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means that in the case of damages 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 the consumer receives 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 at price 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In Rothschild and Stigler (1976)'s model (a very important model we will
 see later in the semester), the consumer is able to purchase partial insurance
 which is denoted as a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\alpha}=[\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the premium and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the insurance coverage---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 the amount of wealth the insurer pays the consumer in case of damages.
 Where appropriate, I'll use this notation below.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that the monopolist doesn't know the consumer's type.
 We assume that the monopolist insurer is profit maximizing and risk neutral.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

: Consumer decides whether to buy or not to buy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $t=3$
\end_inset

: Nature determines outcomes and payoffs are realized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the model above and the assumption of full insurance, consumer
 with insurance will always receive final wealth equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $W-\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 in both states of the world.
 If there are no damages, final payoff is 
\begin_inset Formula $W-\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

; and if there are damages, final payoff is 
\begin_inset Formula $W-d-\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}=W-\alpha_{1}\,(\because\alpha_{2}=d)$
\end_inset

.
 A consumer without insurance will receive 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 in one state and 0 in the other.
 The expected utility of an uninsured consumer is equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
U_{uninsured}(W,\alpha_{1})=(1-p)\sqrt{W}+p\sqrt{0}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the equilibrium price and who buys insurance given the fact that
 the insure does not know the consumer's type (which for purposes of this
 model is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

)? What would happen if there is full information.
 We'll go over the first question, but you should try the second question.
 The equilibrium for the second question is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

first-best
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 outcome and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=p\cdot W$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If insurer sets price equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

, then the consumer will buy insurance iff:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
U_{insured}(W,\alpha_{1}) & \geq & U_{uninsured}(W,\alpha_{1})\\
\sqrt{W-\alpha_{1}} & \geq & (1-p)\sqrt{W}\\
\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}} & \geq & 1-p\\
p & \geq & 1-\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, all consumers buy insurance but insurers get negative profits, which means
 that there is a profitable deviation for the insurer.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=W$
\end_inset

, no one buys insurance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given a price equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

, the probability that a randomly drawn consumer will buy insurance can
 be solved for as follows:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Pr\left(p\geq1-\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\right)=1-\left(1-\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\right)=\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given the probability that a consumer will buy insurance, what is the expected
 profit for the insurer? To solve for the expected profit, we need to calculated
 the expected risk of a consumer who has bought insurance:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{E}\left[p|bought\, insurance\right] & = & \mathbb{E}\left[p\,|\, p\geq1-\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\cdot\left[1+1-\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\right]\\
 & = & 1-\frac{1}{2}\cdot\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Given the consumer's risk as perceived by insurer, the insurer will maximize
 its profits.
 To put this model in the context of the signaling models we discussed before
 Spring Break: from the perspective of the insurer, the consumer (Sender)
 sends a signal (buying insurance) and based on this signal the insurer
 (Receiver) updates its beliefs.
 Therefore, the expected profit of the insurer on the sale of this insurance
 policy is equal to:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbb{E}\left(\pi\right)=\alpha_{1}-W\cdot\mathbb{E}\left[p|bought\, insurance\right]=\alpha_{1}-W\left(1-\frac{1}{2}\cdot\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Therefore, in equilibrium it must be the case that:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{E}\left(\pi\right) & = & \alpha_{1}-W\left(1-\frac{1}{2}\cdot\sqrt{\frac{W-\alpha_{1}}{W}}\right)\geq0\\
 & \Rightarrow & \alpha_{1}\geq\frac{3w}{4}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

If we have competitive markets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=\frac{3w}{4}$
\end_inset

, and only consumers with risk 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 will buy insurance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Adverse Selection in Auctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Short Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Winner's Curse typically refers to auctions in which the value of the item
 is uncertain to the buyers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
oil exploration rights;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
spectrum auctions;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
free agents in sports
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you take an Industrial Organization class, you'll think a lot about this:
 in equilibrium, bidders take winner's curse into account when submitting
 bids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In FCC spectrum auctions in California, PacBell hired Paul Milgrom to give
 seminars on winner's curse to all their competitors.
 The result was that PacBell won the auction at a really good price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model Set-Up
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that players are bidding in a second price auction.
 Assume that player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's estimated value is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

; and that each players' value of the good/service being auctioned has a
 distribution equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $F(v_{i})$
\end_inset

 and the probability density function of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is as provided below.
 Recall that in a second price auction, it is a weakly dominant strategy
 for a player's bid to equal her value (which in this model is a random
 variable).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the expectation of player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's valuation?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbb{E}(v_{i})=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}v_{i}f(v_{i})dv_{i}\]

\end_inset

Let's assume that the probability distribution function of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is as follows:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The graphical representation of the PDF can be found in Appendix A-2.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
f(v_{i})=\begin{cases}
\frac{v_{i}}{25}, & 0\leq v_{i}<5\\
\frac{2}{5}-\frac{v_{i}}{25}, & 5\leq v_{i}\leq10\\
0, & otherwise\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

Given the pdf of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

, we can now calculate the expected value of player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's valuation:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{E}(v_{i}) & = & \int_{0}^{5}\left(v_{i}\cdot\frac{v_{i}}{25}\right)dv_{i}+\int_{5}^{10}\left\{ v_{i}\cdot\left(\frac{2}{5}-\frac{v_{i}}{25}\right)\right\} dv_{i}\\
 & = & \frac{v_{i}^{3}}{75}|_{0}^{5}+\left(\frac{1}{5}v_{i}^{2}-\frac{v_{i}^{3}}{75}\right)|_{5}^{10}=5\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's probability of winning given the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Pr(player\, i\, wins|v_{i})=\Pr(v_{2}<v_{1}|v_{1})=F(v_{1})\]

\end_inset

, which we can solve for by integrating the pdf we solved for above:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that -1 in the cdf is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normalizing variable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which is required so that the probability measure properties are met.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
F(v_{i})=\begin{cases}
\frac{v_{i}^{2}}{50} & ,0\leq v_{i}<5\\
\frac{2}{5}v_{i}-\frac{v_{i}^{2}}{50}-1 & ,5\leq v_{i}\leq10\end{cases}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

